Python Audio Libraries¶

  • Author: Diego Inácio
  • GitHub: github.com/diegoinacio
  • Notebook: audio_libraries.ipynb

Brief overview about some of the main python libraries which promote input and output of digital audio files.

In [1]:
%matplotlib inline
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from IPython.display import Audio
import numpy as np

from _utils import *

1. Scipy¶

Reading and writing audio files using SciPy.

1.1. Installation¶

Install by command line:

>>> conda install scipy

or

>>> pip install scipy

1.2. Input¶

In [2]:
from scipy.io import wavfile
In [3]:
%%time
try:
    fs, x_scipy = wavfile.read('../_data/A4_cello01.wav')
    x_scipy = x_scipy.astype(np.float32)
    x_scipy /= np.abs(x_scipy).max(axis=0)
except:
    print('Can not load audio!')

Wall time: 26 ms
In [4]:
audiovis(x_scipy, fs)

audio stereo
In [5]:
Audio(x_scipy.min(axis=1), rate=fs)
Out[5]:

2. pySoundFile¶

Reading and writing audio files using pySoundFile.

2.1. Installation¶

Install by command line:

>>> conda install -c conda-forge pysoundfile

or

>>> pip install pysoundfile

2.2. Input¶

In [9]:
import soundfile
In [10]:
%%time
try:
    x_soundfile, fs = soundfile.read('../_data/A4_cello01.wav')
except:
    print('Can not load audio!')

Wall time: 9.99 ms
In [11]:
audiovis(x_soundfile, fs)

3. LibROSA¶

Reading and writing audio files using LibROSA.

3.1. Installation¶

Install by command line:

>>> conda install -c conda-forge librosa

or

>>> pip install librosa

3.2. Input¶

In [16]:
import librosa
In [17]:
%%time
try:
    x_librosa, fs = librosa.load('../_data/A4_cello01.wav', mono=False)
    x_librosa = x_librosa.T
except:
    print('Can not load audio!')

Wall time: 704 ms
In [18]:
audiovis(x_librosa, fs)
